      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "WPI versus metres per 100 g",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "UK patterns more often specify yarn weight in metres per 100 g (m/100 g) than in WPI. To find the m/100 g of a hand-spun skein: weigh the skein in grams, measure its total length in metres, then calculate (total length / weight) x 100. A DK hand-spun typically runs 180 to 220 m per 100 g; an aran runs 80 to 120 m per 100 g. Both systems converge on the same result; WPI is faster for a quick in-progress check, m/100 g is more exact for pattern matching.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Worked example",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A spinner produces a 100-g skein that measures 14 WPI. This falls in the DK category (12 to 16 WPI). The skein is 190 m in total, giving 190 m/100 g. A pattern calling for DK at 200 m/100 g will work with this yarn, though the spinner should knit a tension square to confirm gauge before committing to the full project.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
